"## Abstract\nLight field depth estimation in mixed Lambertian and non-Lambertian scenes remains challenging due to conflicting physical imaging cues and specular reflections. Existing approaches struggle to unify these domains and often overlook the fundamental signal-processing limits of angular frequency analysis under sparse sampling. We developed a unified dual-mask physical model that integrated multi-directional epipolar plane image (EPI) and pure defocus cues within a compact 754K-parameter architecture. Crucially, we conducted a rigorous signal-processing analysis that theoretically and empirically falsified the feasibility of angular frequency-domain material classification under standard 9×9 sampling, establishing a minimum 17×17 angular resolution requirement for Nyquist compliance. To mitigate long-tail domain distributions and optimize multi-domain joint training, we introduced domain-balanced sampling and high-resolution scaling strategies. Extensive evaluations across three datasets demonstrate that our model achieves an overall mean absolute error (MAE) of 0.1795, reducing the error by 26% against the baseline and yielding a 41% improvement in non-Lambertian domains. Furthermore, we identify an empirical MAE lower bound of approximately 0.20 for EPI-based architectures in complex Lambertian scenes. This work provides an efficient unified baseline for complex light field depth estimation while delineating the fundamental hardware and architectural boundaries for future epipolar research.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, Non-Lambertian reflectance, Epipolar plane image, Angular frequency analysis, Domain-balanced sampling, Dual-mask physical model"